@pythongiant `view(dtype)` (like `reinterpret_cast` in C++) is different from `to(dtype)` (like `static_cast`), so it needs to be separately implemented in `torch.compile`. Let's see how the PyTorch developers plan to implement this.

Currently I'm working around this using explicit bit manipulation:
https://github.com/woct0rdho/transformers-qwen3-moe-fused/blob/91150b19fb3e7224ddb2d4941e1b9e7f99cc5363/qwen3_moe_fused/quantize_gguf/dequant.py#L59

TorchDynamo generates identical cache keys (CodeID) for factory-wrapped functions (like wrap_compile) because it hashes the __code__ object without hashing the bound closure variables, causing the second compilation (dequantize_blocks_Q6_K) to falsely hit the cache of the first (dequantize_blocks_BF16) and execute with stale static assumptions (e.g. wrong shape/stride constants for view(dtype)).
```Python
// Fix in torch/_dynamo/utils.py (or where CodeID/CacheKey is defined)
class CodeID:
    # ...
    def __hash__(self):
        # Must hash closure cell contents to differentiate instances generated by the same factory
        closure_hash = tuple(hash(c.cell_contents) for c in self.fn.__closure__) if self.fn.__closure__ else ()
        return hash((self.code_hash, closure_hash))

    def __eq__(self, other):
        if not isinstance(other, CodeID): return False
        self_closure = tuple(c.cell_contents for c in self.fn.__closure__) if self.fn.__closure__ else ()
        other_closure = tuple(c.cell_contents for c in other.fn.__closure__) if other.fn.__closure__ else ()
        return self.code_hash == other.code_hash and self_closure == other_closure
```

@krastogi-in 
Code Review & Audit: PR #173512
First off, excellent root-cause analysis. You successfully traced a very stealthy cache-poisoning bug back to its origin: Dynamo treating dynamically generated functions (closures) as identical because it was only hashing the __code__ object. The added test case (test_factory_created_functions_separate_pgo_state) is bulletproof and perfectly isolates the issue.

However, while the fix works for this specific reproducer, there are a couple of system-level edge cases regarding Python's cell semantics and distributed caching that we need to harden before this gets merged into main.

Here is my audit:

1. The ValueError Blast Radius (Cell Empty Exception)
In Python, accessing c.cell_contents on an uninitialized cell doesn't return None; it raises ValueError: Cell is empty.
In your implementation:

```Python
try:
    closure_hash = hash(
        tuple(
            _get_closure_content(c.cell_contents)
            if hasattr(c, "cell_contents")
            else None
            for c in closure
        )
    )
except ValueError:
    pass
```
Because the try...except wraps the entire tuple comprehension, if even one cell in the closure is uninitialized, the exception is thrown, the comprehension aborts, and closure_hash silently falls back to None. This leaves the function vulnerable to the exact same cache collision bug we are trying to fix if it happens to have mixed initialized/uninitialized cells.

Fix: Handle the ValueError on a per-cell basis.

2. The Ephemerality of id() and Remote PGO
In _get_closure_content:

```Python
def _get_closure_content(content: types.CellType) -> object:
    if callable(content) and hasattr(content, "__code__"):
        return content.__code__
    return id(content)
```
Using id(content) is a classic trap in caching layers. id() is tied to the memory address of the object, which is strictly tied to the lifecycle of the current Python process.
If a user is leveraging Remote PGO (which relies on CodeId to serialize state across distributed nodes or disk caches—see automatic_dynamic_remote_pgo in pgo.py), id() will result in non-deterministic hashes across different runs. This will cause remote cache misses and trigger silent recompilations.

Fix: If the object isn't a code object, attempt to hash its actual value (if it is immutable/hashable) before falling back to id(). We want to preserve determinism as much as possible for remote caches.

Suggested Code Refactoring
Here is a hardened version of your logic that handles both the per-cell ValueError and improves the determinism of the hash:

```Python
def _get_closure_content(content: Any) -> object:
    if callable(content) and hasattr(content, "__code__"):
        return content.__code__

    # Attempt to use the actual value for deterministic cross-process caching (Remote PGO).
    # Fallback to id() ONLY for unhashable types (like dicts, lists) where memory identity is the only option.
    try:
        hash(content)
        return content
    except TypeError:
        return id(content)

def _get_cell_hash_content(c: types.CellType) -> Any:
    # Safely extract cell contents without blowing up the entire tuple hash
    try:
        return _get_closure_content(c.cell_contents)
    except ValueError:
        # Raised if the cell is completely empty
        return None

@dataclasses.dataclass(frozen=True)
class CodeId:
    # ... [keep existing properties] ...

    @staticmethod
    def make(
        code: types.CodeType, closure: Optional[tuple[types.CellType, ...]] = None
    ) -> "CodeId":
        closure_hash = None
        if closure:
            # Safely hash the closure tuple, isolating exceptions per-cell
            closure_hash = hash(tuple(_get_cell_hash_content(c) for c in closure))

        return CodeId(
            filename=code.co_filename,
            firstlineno=code.co_firstlineno,
            name=code.co_name,
            file_hash=_hash_containing_file(code.co_filename),
            closure_hash=closure_hash,
        )
```
Summary
The PR is fundamentally correct in its approach.

Update the ValueError handling to prevent the whole hash generation from aborting.

Patch id() to prioritize actual object hashing for remote cache determinism.

Drop these updates in, and from an engineering perspective, this is a beautiful fix to a nasty bug. Great job tracking this down!

@eellison I agree. But if this unbacked int is data dependent, we need a way to make any operations related to it cudagraph unsafe..

In the vLLM use-case specifically, we don't want to skip all dynamic sizes as we mark the batch size as dynamic and then we'd be skipping the whole graph. We might also transition the batch size to unbacked in the future so if we do that we need a way to distinguish between the batch size (cudagraph safe) and the split point (cudagraph unsafe).

The most general solution would be to have a way of "tagging"  unbacked and dynamic ints as cudagraph safe/unsafe. That way users can directly decide which dims are cudagraph safe and which aren't.

@laithsakka 
> torch._dynamo.set_cudagraph_capturable(s0/u0, True/False)?

My concern is that users may not know which s0/u0 to mark. It might be fine for s0 as `mark_dynamic`. But it's a bit hard to know exactly the name as u0 (or some other number like u1728). Maybe it's easier to mark a custom op such that all of its output symints are cudagraph unsafe?

> when s0 is not cudagraph_capturable, we will not skip the whole graph that have it if graph_partition=False, if graph_partition=True we will wsplit it, namely find the maximal subgraph that does not include s0 and CUDA-graph that part.

IIUC this config should only have impact on inductor graph partition. Inductor graph partition identifies all ops that use these cg-unsafe symints and splits these ops outside graph partitions.


